In .NET MAUI Shell, override `OnBackButtonPressed` on your page and use `Shell.BackButtonBehavior` for the custom button:

**1. Intercept hardware/software back navigation:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
            ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
            return true; // cancel navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ShowUnsavedChangesDialog()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**2. Custom "Cancel" back button in XAML:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior
            TextOverride="Cancel"
            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

**3. ViewModel command (if using MVVM):**

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles Android hardware back and Shell's nav-bar back. Return `true` to cancel.
- `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` replaces the arrow with "Cancel" text. You can also set `IconOverride` for a custom icon.
- The `Command` on `BackButtonBehavior` replaces the default back action entirely, so you must call `GoToAsync("..")` yourself.
- On **iOS**, the swipe-back gesture bypasses `OnBackButtonPressed` — set `BackButtonBehavior.IsVisible="True"` and consider disabling the gesture via a platform-specific handler if full interception is needed.
